    <name>
      <text>8.1.21 (Arith. seq. savings 2)</text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<p>Alice started a new job and earned £\({@earn1@}\) in her first month. Thereafter, her salary increased by £\({@salincy@}\) per year. Her expenses are £\({@expy1@}\) during the first year and the expenses increase by £\({@expincy@}\) per year. How many years will it take for Alice to save £\({@save@}\) per month? Give your answer to the nearest year.</p>

<p>[[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]]</p>]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<p>Begin by turning everything into a monthly timetable. Alice's salary increases by £\({@salincy@}/12 =\) £\({@salincm@}\) per month. Similarly, Alices expenses increase by \({@expincy@}/12\) = £\({@expincm@}\) per month.</p>

<p>Next we can write both the expenses and salary as a monthly sequence:
\[
\begin{align*}
&\mbox{salary}: {@earn1@},{@earn1+salincm@}, {@earn1+salincm*2@}, \dots
\\
&\mbox{savings}: {@expy1@},{@expy1+ expincm@}, {@expy1+ expincm@}, \dots
\end{align*}
\]
We can subtract the second sequence from the first which will give us a sequence of how much Alice saves every month. We have:
\[
{@sav1@},{@sav1+dd@},{@sav1+2*dd@}, \dots.
\]
We notice that this sequence is an arithmetic sequence because each term is increasing by \({@dd@}\) per month. Therefore we can write a formula for the sequence as
\[
u_n = a + (n-1)d = {@sav1@} + {@dd@}(n-1).
\]
To find which month Alice saves £\({@save@}\) we substitute \(u_n = {@save@}\) into the formula above and rearrange to get \(n\). So we have 
\[
{@save@} = {@sav1@} + {@dd@}(n-1) \implies {@save-sav1@}/{@dd@} + 1 = n = {@months@}.
\] 
Thus it takes Alice \({@months@}\) months to save £\({@save@}\) or in years, it takes her \({@months@}/12 \approx {@ta1@}\) years.</p>]]></text>
    </generalfeedback>
